Introduction to R - Exercises

CCDL for ALSF

2020

The goal of these exercises is to help you get comfortable with using R and R notebooks by continuing to play with the gene results dataset we used in the 01-intro_to_base_R and 02-intro_to_ggplot2 notebooks. It is a pre-processed astrocytoma microarray dataset on which we performed a set of differential expression analyses.

We’ll want to establish a directory called results/ to save our results from this exercise. In the following chunk, ensure that this directory exists as follows:

  • First, define a variable results_dir with the value "results". This is the name of the directory we’ll create.
  • Next, create this directory with fs::dir_create(). Note that this function will not do anything if that directory already exists, so it is safe to run anytime.
# define a results_dir variable
results_dir <- "results"
# create the results directory
fs::dir_create(results_dir)

Read in the gene results file

Use readr::read_tsv() to read in the file “gene_results_GSE44971.tsv” and assign it the variable stats_df. Recall that this notation means the read_tsv() function from the readr package. If you have already loaded the tidyverse package above with library(), you can use the function read_tsv() on its own without the preceding readr:: as the readr package is loaded as part of tidyverse.

stats_df <- read_tsv("data/gene_results_GSE44971.tsv")

Create a density plot

Set up a ggplot object for astrocytoma_normal_df and set x as the average expression variable. Use the + to add on a layer called geom_density()

Use the plot you started above and add a ggplot2::theme layer to play with its aesthetics (e.g. theme_classic()) See the ggplot2 themes vignette to see a list of theme options.

Feel free to make other customizations to this plot by adding more layers with +. You can start by adding labels with the function labs(), and then by getting inspiration from this handy cheatsheet for ggplot2 (PDF).

Save your plot as a PNG.
